  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "However, this task-centric optimization approach may introduce fairness concerns, primarily attributed to the indiscriminate transmission of information into the condensed graph.",
    "Especially in scenarios with intensive compression rates, GC tends to amplify biases as it prioritizes the preservation of predominant and representative information w.r.t the tasks.",
    "Consequently, GNNs trained on condensed graphs exhibit more severe fairness issues than those trained on original graphs [51], [52] and challenge the applicability of GC in high-stake applications [84], [51].To mitigate bias in condensed graphs, FGD [51] initially investigates the relationship between the feature spaces of the original graph and condensed graph, and constructs an estimator for sensitive features.",
    "Following this, the variance of the estimated sensitive group membership is employed as the bias measurement and integrated as the regularization to facilitate the unbiased condensed graph.",
    "Moreover, GCARe [52] directly regularizes the condensation process with adversarial training."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "Consequently, GNNs trained on condensed graphs exhibit more severe fairness issues than those trained on original graphs [51], [52] and challenge the applicability of GC in high-stake applications [84], [51].To mitigate bias in condensed graphs, FGD [51] initially investigates the relationship between the feature spaces of the original graph and condensed graph, and constructs an estimator for sensitive features.",
    "Moreover, GCARe [52] directly regularizes the condensation process with adversarial training."
  ]
